1
00:00:01,664 --> 00:00:05,903
Let's take a look at what the K-means
clustering algorithm does.

2
00:00:05,903 --> 00:00:08,224
Let me start with an example.

3
00:00:08,224 --> 00:00:13,218
Here I've plotted a data set with
30 unlabeled training examples.

4
00:00:13,218 --> 00:00:15,294
So there are 30 points.

5
00:00:15,294 --> 00:00:19,752
And what we like to do is run
K-means on this data set.

6
00:00:19,752 --> 00:00:25,440
The first thing that the K-means algorithm
does is it will take a random guess

7
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:31,142
at where might be the centers of the two
clusters that you might ask it to find.

8
00:00:31,142 --> 00:00:36,120
In this example I'm going to ask
it to try to find two clusters.

9
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:38,647
Later in this week we'll talk about how

10
00:00:38,647 --> 00:00:41,487
you might decide how
many clusters to find.

11
00:00:41,487 --> 00:00:46,660
But the very first step is it
will randomly pick two points,

12
00:00:46,660 --> 00:00:51,520
which I've shown here as a red cross and
the blue cross,

13
00:00:51,520 --> 00:00:56,186
at where might be the centers
of two different clusters.

14
00:00:56,186 --> 00:01:00,383
This is just a random initial guess and
they're not particularly good guesses.

15
00:01:00,383 --> 00:01:02,209
But it's a start.

16
00:01:02,209 --> 00:01:07,005
One thing I hope you take away from
this video is that K-means will

17
00:01:07,005 --> 00:01:09,805
repeatedly do two different things.

18
00:01:09,805 --> 00:01:13,273
The first is assign points
to cluster centroids and

19
00:01:13,273 --> 00:01:15,941
the second is move cluster centroids.

20
00:01:15,941 --> 00:01:18,130
Let's take a look at what this means.

21
00:01:18,130 --> 00:01:25,185
The first of the two steps is it will
go through each of these points and

22
00:01:25,185 --> 00:01:31,767
look at whether it is closer to
the red cross or to the blue cross.

23
00:01:31,767 --> 00:01:36,669
The very first thing that K-means
does is it will take a random guess

24
00:01:36,669 --> 00:01:39,602
at where are the centers of the cluster?

25
00:01:39,602 --> 00:01:45,493
And the centers of the cluster
are called cluster centroids.

26
00:01:45,493 --> 00:01:50,379
After it's made an initial guess
at where the cluster centroid is,

27
00:01:50,379 --> 00:01:57,082
it will go through all of these examples,
x(1) through x(30), my 30 data points.

28
00:01:57,082 --> 00:02:02,019
And for each of them it will check if it
is closer to the red cluster centroid,

29
00:02:02,019 --> 00:02:06,725
shown by the red cross, or if it's
closer to the blue cluster centroid,

30
00:02:06,725 --> 00:02:08,371
shown by the blue cross.

31
00:02:08,371 --> 00:02:13,071
And it will assign each of these
points to whichever of the cluster

32
00:02:13,071 --> 00:02:15,044
centroids It is closer to.

33
00:02:15,044 --> 00:02:19,916
I'm going to illustrate that by
painting each of these examples,

34
00:02:19,916 --> 00:02:24,788
each of these little round dots,
either red or blue, depending on

35
00:02:24,788 --> 00:02:30,185
whether that example is closer to
the red or to the blue cluster centroid.

36
00:02:30,185 --> 00:02:34,371
So this point up here is closer to the red
centroid, which is why it's painted red.

37
00:02:34,371 --> 00:02:39,063
Whereas this point down there is
closer to the blue cluster centroid,

38
00:02:39,063 --> 00:02:41,696
which is why I've now painted it blue.

39
00:02:41,696 --> 00:02:47,576
So that was the first of the two things
that K-means does over and over.

40
00:02:47,576 --> 00:02:50,277
Which is a sign points
to clusters centroids.

41
00:02:50,277 --> 00:02:55,582
And all that means is it will associate
which I'm illustrating with the color,

42
00:02:55,582 --> 00:02:58,600
every point of one of
the cluster centroids.

43
00:02:58,600 --> 00:03:02,926
The second of the two steps
that K-means does is,

44
00:03:02,926 --> 00:03:08,396
it'll look at all of the red points and
take an average of them.

45
00:03:08,396 --> 00:03:13,249
And it will move the red cross
to whatever is the average

46
00:03:13,249 --> 00:03:18,010
location of the red dots,
which turns out to be here.

47
00:03:18,010 --> 00:03:23,125
And so the red cross, that is the red
cluster centroid will move here.

48
00:03:23,125 --> 00:03:25,559
And then we do the same thing for
all the blue dots.

49
00:03:25,559 --> 00:03:29,604
Look at all the blue dots, and
take an average of them, and

50
00:03:29,604 --> 00:03:31,842
move the blue cross over there.

51
00:03:31,842 --> 00:03:37,878
So you now have a new location for
the blue cluster centroid as well.

52
00:03:37,878 --> 00:03:41,730
In the next video we'll look at
the mathematical formulas for

53
00:03:41,730 --> 00:03:43,590
how to do both of these steps.

54
00:03:43,590 --> 00:03:48,451
But now that you have these new and
hopefully slightly improved guesses for

55
00:03:48,451 --> 00:03:51,305
the locations of the to cluster centroids,

56
00:03:51,305 --> 00:03:55,333
we'll look through all of
the 30 training examples again.

57
00:03:55,333 --> 00:03:59,716
And check for every one of them,
whether it's closer to the red or

58
00:03:59,716 --> 00:04:03,074
the blue cluster centroid for
the new locations.

59
00:04:03,074 --> 00:04:08,100
And then we will associate them which
are indicated by the color again,

60
00:04:08,100 --> 00:04:11,298
every point to the closer
cluster centroid.

61
00:04:11,298 --> 00:04:15,469
And if you do that, you see that
the field points change color.

62
00:04:15,469 --> 00:04:18,466
So for example, this point is colored red,

63
00:04:18,466 --> 00:04:22,767
because it was closer to the red
cluster centroid previously.

64
00:04:22,767 --> 00:04:25,770
But if we now look again,
it's now actually closer to

65
00:04:25,770 --> 00:04:30,533
the blue cluster centroid, because the
blue and red cluster centroids have moved.

66
00:04:30,533 --> 00:04:35,078
So if we go through and
associate each point with the closer

67
00:04:35,078 --> 00:04:38,430
cluster centroids, you end up with this.

68
00:04:38,430 --> 00:04:42,636
And then we just repeat
the second part of K-means again.

69
00:04:42,636 --> 00:04:48,941
Which is look at all of the red dots and
compute the average.

70
00:04:48,941 --> 00:04:51,387
And also look at all of the blue dots and

71
00:04:51,387 --> 00:04:54,838
compute the average location
of all of the blue dots.

72
00:04:54,838 --> 00:05:00,314
And it turns out that you end up
moving the red cross over there and

73
00:05:00,314 --> 00:05:02,552
the blue cross over here.

74
00:05:02,552 --> 00:05:03,769
And we repeat.

75
00:05:03,769 --> 00:05:06,858
Let's look at all of the points again and
we color them,

76
00:05:06,858 --> 00:05:11,078
either red or blue, depending on which
cluster centroid that is closer to.

77
00:05:11,078 --> 00:05:13,087
So you end up with this.

78
00:05:13,087 --> 00:05:18,083
And then again, look at all of the red
dots and take their average location,

79
00:05:18,083 --> 00:05:22,219
and look at all the blue dots and
take the average location, and

80
00:05:22,219 --> 00:05:24,898
move the clusters to the new locations.

81
00:05:24,898 --> 00:05:29,634
And it turns out that if you were to keep
on repeating these two steps, that is

82
00:05:29,634 --> 00:05:34,370
look at each point and assign it to
the nearest cluster centroid and then also

83
00:05:34,370 --> 00:05:39,108
move each cluster centroid to the mean
of all the points with the same color.

84
00:05:39,108 --> 00:05:43,788
If you keep on doing those two steps,
you find that there are no more changes to

85
00:05:43,788 --> 00:05:48,120
the colors of the points or to
the locations of the clusters centroids.

86
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:52,968
And so this means that at this point
the K-means clustering algorithm has

87
00:05:52,968 --> 00:05:53,838
converged.

88
00:05:53,838 --> 00:05:58,525
Because applying those two steps over and
over, results in no further

89
00:05:58,525 --> 00:06:02,577
changes to either the assignment
to point to the centroids or

90
00:06:02,577 --> 00:06:05,286
the location of the cluster centroids.

91
00:06:05,286 --> 00:06:09,445
In this example, it looks like
K-means has done a pretty good job.

92
00:06:09,445 --> 00:06:14,780
It has found that these points up
here correspond to one cluster,

93
00:06:14,780 --> 00:06:19,634
and these points down here
correspond to a second cluster.

94
00:06:19,634 --> 00:06:24,073
So now you've seen an illustration
of how K-means works.

95
00:06:24,073 --> 00:06:28,538
The two key steps are, assign every
point to the cluster centroid,

96
00:06:28,538 --> 00:06:31,921
depending on what cluster
centroid is nearest to.

97
00:06:31,921 --> 00:06:35,867
And second move each cluster
centroid to the average or

98
00:06:35,867 --> 00:06:39,569
the mean of all the points
that were assigned to it.

99
00:06:39,569 --> 00:06:42,999
In the next video,
we'll look at how to formalize this and

100
00:06:42,999 --> 00:06:46,857
write out the algorithm that does
what you just saw in this video.

101
00:06:46,857 --> 00:06:48,661
